track_notes: A rough track (OK for normal car if driven carefully) takes you to the car park for the walk to Colt Hill at NX 702971. Locked gate then on to the track to the summit. The Andy Goldsworthy Striding Arch at the Cairnhead Barn (near car park)is worth looking at before or after the activation. The walk is on graded forestry tracks up to the junction at 69299 and is suitable for a bike. From there a steeper rougher track (could not be ridden) goes up steeper for 500m distance to the summit and the Striding Arch. Return the same way. WE walked it there and back and easily qualified on 2m FM with 40 watts and a dipole.
track_title: Walk up to one of the Striding Arches

track_notes:
I parked on the roadside. There are a number of places, it is your choice how much road walk at the beginning or end of the day. I did not see any No Overnight notices so if you have the facilities / vehicle it would be a nice valley to park in and avoid the morning drive.

A bit of detour to the Byre Striding Arch. I used the forest track where possible. 

On the route to Wether Hill you leave the forest track and head up the Dibbing Lane then up the valley side to the fire lookout. This was a bit hard going. I should have tried to get on the forest road up to the lookout point earlier.

With a bit more planning I could have taken in the Striding Arch at Benbrack.

I had to find a broken section of wall at the end to get to Glenjaan Burn and cross Cairn Water. The walk was in dry weather so the stream crossing was easy. In wet weather it could be more difficult.
track_title: Colt Hill and Wether Hill trip
